{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_KljAXWv6S7neROgThZyFph3A","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tid: plan_app\n3\toutput:\n4\t  title: string\n5\t  purpose: string\n6\t  tables: array\n7\t  endpoints: array\n8\t  components: array\n9\t  pages: array\n10\tdependsOn: [read_sources]\n11\trole: general\n12\tfunctions: []\n13\t---\n14\t\n15\tDesign the WHOLE app holistically before any file is written. `query` and `read_sources` (the\n16\tsource-derived build brief in `read_sources.summary`) are in scope. This is the THINKING step: reason\n17\tfrom the material into a concrete shape, then resolve the plan object. You have no file writers here —\n18\tjust produce the high-level lists that the per-category planners below will refine.\n19\t\n20\tSubstitute REAL values derived from the material for every `<…>` (never leave a placeholder). Plan for\n21\tan app the user OPENS: enough tables to hold every kind of record the source contains, endpoints to\n22\tread them, a few REUSABLE components (a card, a row, a stat) that repeat across pages, and MULTIPLE\n23\tpages — an `index` home plus the list/detail/dashboard views the material calls for. Emit one\n24\tstatement:\n25\t\n26\t```typescript\n27\tcurrentTask.resolve({\n28\t  title: '<human-readable app title>',\n29\t  purpose: '<one sentence: what the user opens this app to do>',\n30\t  // High-level only; plan_tables refines schemas + rows.\n31\t  tables: [ { name: '<table_slug>', purpose: '<what it stores, from the source>' } ],\n32\t  // Each route encodes its HTTP method last, e.g. 'items-list/GET'. Methods: GET|POST|PUT|PATCH|DELETE.\n33\t  endpoints: [ { route: '<name>/GET', purpose: '<what it returns or does>' } ],\n34\t  // Reusable UI the pages share — a card/row/badge/stat, PascalCase name.\n35\t  components: [ { name: '<ComponentName>', purpose: '<the repeated UI it renders>' } ],\n36\t  // Use 'index' for the home; add list/detail/dashboard pages the material needs.\n37\t  pages: [ { route: 'index', purpose: '<what the home shows>' } ],\n38\t});\n39\t```\n40\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"77ab428b-0827-4b0f-9cdb-3f06c26238c4","uuid":"178de2ac-fc00-49c1-9260-2ec73fed8c8b","timestamp":"2026-07-16T19:29:00.447Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/libs/core/system-spaces/system-appbuilder/tasklists/build_live_project/02-plan_app.md","content":"---\nid: plan_app\noutput:\n  title: string\n  purpose: string\n  tables: array\n  endpoints: array\n  components: array\n  pages: array\ndependsOn: [read_sources]\nrole: general\nfunctions: []\n---\n\nDesign the WHOLE app holistically before any file is written. `query` and `read_sources` (the\nsource-derived build brief in `read_sources.summary`) are in scope. This is the THINKING step: reason\nfrom the material into a concrete shape, then resolve the plan object. You have no file writers here —\njust produce the high-level lists that the per-category planners below will refine.\n\nSubstitute REAL values derived from the material for every `<…>` (never leave a placeholder). Plan for\nan app the user OPENS: enough tables to hold every kind of record the source contains, endpoints to\nread them, a few REUSABLE components (a card, a row, a stat) that repeat across pages, and MULTIPLE\npages — an `index` home plus the list/detail/dashboard views the material calls for. Emit one\nstatement:\n\n```typescript\ncurrentTask.resolve({\n  title: '<human-readable app title>',\n  purpose: '<one sentence: what the user opens this app to do>',\n  // High-level only; plan_tables refines schemas + rows.\n  tables: [ { name: '<table_slug>', purpose: '<what it stores, from the source>' } ],\n  // Each route encodes its HTTP method last, e.g. 'items-list/GET'. Methods: GET|POST|PUT|PATCH|DELETE.\n  endpoints: [ { route: '<name>/GET', purpose: '<what it returns or does>' } ],\n  // Reusable UI the pages share — a card/row/badge/stat, PascalCase name.\n  components: [ { name: '<ComponentName>', purpose: '<the repeated UI it renders>' } ],\n  // Use 'index' for the home; add list/detail/dashboard pages the material needs.\n  pages: [ { route: 'index', purpose: '<what the home shows>' } ],\n});\n```\n","numLines":40,"startLine":1,"totalLines":40}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_NIHqAki7Zx3xLL2bYmc2Sm3v","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tid: plan_endpoints\n3\toutput:\n4\t  endpoints: array\n5\tdependsOn: [plan_app, plan_tables]\n6\trole: general\n7\tfunctions: []\n8\t---\n9\t\n10\tRefine the endpoint list GROUNDED in the real tables, and ASSIGN each endpoint its stable `name` — the\n11\tsingle source of truth the whole app wires through. `query`, `plan_app` (`plan_app.endpoints`), and\n12\t`plan_tables` (`plan_tables.tables` — the actual tables + columns being written) are in scope. This is\n13\ta THINKING step — no writers. Plan the endpoints the pages need to read/write the real rows: at least\n14\tone read endpoint per view the app shows.\n15\t\n16\tEach endpoint is `{ name, route, purpose, tables }`:\n17\t- `name` — a UNIQUE lowercase-hyphen id (e.g. `cost-lines`, `contacts-list`, `itinerary-legs`). This\n18\t  EXACT string is BOTH the endpoint module's `export const name` AND what pages pass to `useApi(...)`.\n19\t  **This is the ONLY node that assigns names; every downstream node uses them verbatim and never\n20\t  re-derives one.** No two endpoints may share a `name`, and no two may share a `route` — scan your own\n21\t  list before resolving and rename any collision.\n22\t- `route` — the file route with its HTTP method LAST (`cost-lines/GET`, `bookings/[id]/PATCH`); methods\n23\t  GET|POST|PUT|PATCH|DELETE.\n24\t- `tables` — the table name(s) from `plan_tables.tables` it reads/writes.\n25\t\n26\tRead endpoints return `{ items: [...] }`, so plan read endpoints the pages consume as `data.items`.\n27\tEmit one statement:\n28\t\n29\t```typescript\n30\tcurrentTask.resolve({\n31\t  endpoints: [\n32\t    { name: '<unique-hyphen-id>', route: '<path>/GET', purpose: '<what it returns or does>', tables: [ '<table from plan_tables.tables>' ] },\n33\t  ],\n34\t});\n35\t```\n36\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"77ab428b-0827-4b0f-9cdb-3f06c26238c4","uuid":"00e0210c-fe03-4190-b1d4-71e07e97051a","timestamp":"2026-07-16T19:29:00.448Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/libs/core/system-spaces/system-appbuilder/tasklists/build_live_project/05-plan_endpoints.md","content":"---\nid: plan_endpoints\noutput:\n  endpoints: array\ndependsOn: [plan_app, plan_tables]\nrole: general\nfunctions: []\n---\n\nRefine the endpoint list GROUNDED in the real tables, and ASSIGN each endpoint its stable `name` — the\nsingle source of truth the whole app wires through. `query`, `plan_app` (`plan_app.endpoints`), and\n`plan_tables` (`plan_tables.tables` — the actual tables + columns being written) are in scope. This is\na THINKING step — no writers. Plan the endpoints the pages need to read/write the real rows: at least\none read endpoint per view the app shows.\n\nEach endpoint is `{ name, route, purpose, tables }`:\n- `name` — a UNIQUE lowercase-hyphen id (e.g. `cost-lines`, `contacts-list`, `itinerary-legs`). This\n  EXACT string is BOTH the endpoint module's `export const name` AND what pages pass to `useApi(...)`.\n  **This is the ONLY node that assigns names; every downstream node uses them verbatim and never\n  re-derives one.** No two endpoints may share a `name`, and no two may share a `route` — scan your own\n  list before resolving and rename any collision.\n- `route` — the file route with its HTTP method LAST (`cost-lines/GET`, `bookings/[id]/PATCH`); methods\n  GET|POST|PUT|PATCH|DELETE.\n- `tables` — the table name(s) from `plan_tables.tables` it reads/writes.\n\nRead endpoints return `{ items: [...] }`, so plan read endpoints the pages consume as `data.items`.\nEmit one statement:\n\n```typescript\ncurrentTask.resolve({\n  endpoints: [\n    { name: '<unique-hyphen-id>', route: '<path>/GET', purpose: '<what it returns or does>', tables: [ '<table from plan_tables.tables>' ] },\n  ],\n});\n```\n","numLines":36,"startLine":1,"totalLines":36}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_3jp6frFuilvpHm09DWGhURri","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tid: plan_tables\n3\toutput:\n4\t  tables: array\n5\tdependsOn: [plan_app, read_sources]\n6\trole: general\n7\tfunctions: []\n8\t---\n9\t\n10\tTurn the holistic table list into a DETAILED, source-grounded data model. `query`, `read_sources`\n11\t(the build brief), and `plan_app` (`plan_app.tables` is the high-level list) are in scope. This is\n12\tstill a THINKING step — no writers here. For every table produce its full `schema` AND the actual\n13\t`rows` read from the material, so the implement step can seed data at creation. Do NOT invent rows: use\n14\tonly values the source states (identifiers, contacts, dates, payments, stated totals, attribution). If\n15\tthe source has no rows for a table, drop that table — a created-but-empty table is the #1 failure.\n16\t\n17\tEvery table schema needs a `title`, a `description`, and `columns` where each column has a\n18\t`description` and exactly one uuid primary key. Keys in each row object MUST match the column names.\n19\tEmit one statement:\n20\t\n21\t```typescript\n22\tcurrentTask.resolve({\n23\t  tables: [\n24\t    {\n25\t      name: '<source-derived table name>',\n26\t      schema: {\n27\t        title: '<Title>',\n28\t        description: '<what this table stores>',\n29\t        columns: {\n30\t          id: { type: 'string', description: 'Primary key', primaryKey: true, generated: 'uuid' },\n31\t          // …one column per field the record carries, each with a real description.\n32\t        },\n33\t      },\n34\t      // One object per record READ FROM THE MATERIAL. Never carry over an example value.\n35\t      rows: [ /* { id: '…', …source-derived fields } */ ],\n36\t    },\n37\t  ],\n38\t});\n39\t```\n40\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"77ab428b-0827-4b0f-9cdb-3f06c26238c4","uuid":"48cf3216-e5ab-45f9-84ea-fdaf626ef2d8","timestamp":"2026-07-16T19:29:00.449Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/libs/core/system-spaces/system-appbuilder/tasklists/build_live_project/03-plan_tables.md","content":"---\nid: plan_tables\noutput:\n  tables: array\ndependsOn: [plan_app, read_sources]\nrole: general\nfunctions: []\n---\n\nTurn the holistic table list into a DETAILED, source-grounded data model. `query`, `read_sources`\n(the build brief), and `plan_app` (`plan_app.tables` is the high-level list) are in scope. This is\nstill a THINKING step — no writers here. For every table produce its full `schema` AND the actual\n`rows` read from the material, so the implement step can seed data at creation. Do NOT invent rows: use\nonly values the source states (identifiers, contacts, dates, payments, stated totals, attribution). If\nthe source has no rows for a table, drop that table — a created-but-empty table is the #1 failure.\n\nEvery table schema needs a `title`, a `description`, and `columns` where each column has a\n`description` and exactly one uuid primary key. Keys in each row object MUST match the column names.\nEmit one statement:\n\n```typescript\ncurrentTask.resolve({\n  tables: [\n    {\n      name: '<source-derived table name>',\n      schema: {\n        title: '<Title>',\n        description: '<what this table stores>',\n        columns: {\n          id: { type: 'string', description: 'Primary key', primaryKey: true, generated: 'uuid' },\n          // …one column per field the record carries, each with a real description.\n        },\n      },\n      // One object per record READ FROM THE MATERIAL. Never carry over an example value.\n      rows: [ /* { id: '…', …source-derived fields } */ ],\n    },\n  ],\n});\n```\n","numLines":40,"startLine":1,"totalLines":40}}}
